Locked architectural decisions
1. Verification validates the complete Execution Trust Record

Verification is not selective.

Every verification validates:

Business Transaction
Metadata
Policy
Signals
Decision
Override History
Execution History
Evidence
Receipt
2. Verification is read-only

Verification never modifies:

Business Transaction
Decision
Override
Execution
Receipt

It only evaluates their integrity and consistency.

3. Verification is append-only

Each verification creates a new Verification artifact.

Verification history becomes part of the Execution Trust Record and supports long-term auditability.

4. Overall result

verified represents the final outcome:

true — every required trust artifact passed verification.
false — one or more trust artifacts failed verification.

The checks object provides detailed results for each trust artifact.

5. Independent verification

The Verification artifact records the outcome of a verification operation.

Independent verifiers can reproduce the same result using:

the Execution Trust Record,
the Receipt,
Parmana's public verification key,
the recorded policy version,
the recorded schema version.
Canonical Principle (Locked)

Verification is a deterministic, read-only validation of the complete Execution Trust Record.

It produces an immutable Verification artifact that records the integrity and consistency of every trust artifact without modifying the underlying Business Transaction or its execution history.


